  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA278-kiḷavi">itu tōḻi talaimakaṭku varaivu malintatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante rejoiced at HER marriage.</p>
        </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA278">
<l>            paṭukāḻ nāṟiya parāaraip puṉṉai</l>
<l>            yaṭumaraṉ mokkuḷi ṉirumpuvā yaviḻap</l>
<l>            poṉṉi ṉaṉṉa tātupaṭu paṉmalar</l>
<l>            cūṭunar toṭutta miccil kōṭutoṟu</l>
<l>            neykaṉi pacuṅkāy tūṅkun tuṟaivaṉai </l>
<l>            yiṉiyaṟin ticiṉē koṇka ṉākutal</l>
<l>            kaḻiccē ṟāṭiya kaṇaikkā lattiri</l>
<l>            kuḷampiṉuñ cēyiṟā voṭuṅkiṉa</l>
<l>            kōtaiyu mellā mūtaiveṇ maṇalē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Know<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṟinticiṉ</term>: this form unmarked for person can be used at least for the 1st and the 2nd sg., and since here we have no clarifying pronoun <term xml:lang="ta">yāṉ</term>, I had rather take it as an imperative. T.V.G., however, reads a 1st person.</note> now that he will become [your] husband,</l>
<l>the man from the ghat,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where green unripe fruit becoming soft with oil hang</l>
<l rend="indent">on every branch, the rest after those wearing [garlands] had linked</l>
<l rend="indent">many blossoms full of gold-like pollen,</l>
<l rend="indent2">when the large-trunked Puṉṉai tree fragrant in [its] developing(?) core</l>
<l rend="indent2">opened [its] iron mouths, as the flower-buds of the near bowstring hemp.</l>
<l rend="indent">More than the prawn shrank under the hoofs</l>
<l rend="indent">of the mule with round legs that played in the mud of the backwaters</l>
<l>all the garlands<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kōtai-y-um ellām</term>: why the double marking with -<term xml:lang="ta">um</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">ellām</term>?</note> [shrank] under the sand [blown] by the cold wind.<note place="foot">This sentence is a problem, since the relations are nowhere marked clearly. The last line is completely free from verb forms, so supposedly the verb of the last line has to be read here, too. The <term xml:lang="ta">kuḷampiṉum</term> seems to be marked as a comparative which is strange, for the translation given above would actually presuppose a comparative mark on the <term xml:lang="ta">iṟā</term>. The point seems to be, nevertheless, that HE is coming with utmost despatch to fulfil his promise.</note></l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
